  "prompt": "What are the basic key points of India's Companies Act 2013?",
  "response": "Here are the key points of India's Companies Act 2013:\n\n1. Corporate Governance\n- Mandatory independent directors\n- Enhanced disclosure requirements\n- Stricter compliance norms\n- Increased corporate accountability\n\n2. Company Formation\n- Simplified incorporation process\n- Reduced minimum capital requirements\n- One-person company concept introduced\n- Online registration facilities\n\n3. Directors' Responsibilities\n- Enhanced roles and responsibilities\n- Mandatory director identification number (DIN)\n- Qualification and disqualification criteria\n- Restriction on number of directorship positions\n\n4. Board Composition\n- Minimum number of directors specified\n- Mandatory women directors for certain companies\n- Regular board meetings requirement\n- Rotation of independent directors\n\n5. Financial Transparency\n- Mandatory financial reporting\n- Stricter audit regulations\n- Enhanced corporate financial disclosure\n- Internal financial control mechanisms\n\n6. Shareholder Rights\n- Enhanced shareholder protection\n- Voting rights and representation\n- Class action suits\n- Minority shareholder protection\n\n7. Corporate Social Responsibility (CSR)\n- Mandatory CSR spending for eligible companies\n- Specific CSR expenditure guidelines\n- Reporting and compliance requirements\n\n8. Penalties and Enforcement\n- Stringent penalties for non-compliance\n- Stronger regulatory mechanisms\n- Enhanced investigative powers\n- Simplified dispute resolution processes\n\nThese points represent the fundamental aspects of the Companies Act 2013.",
